I have a TextureAtlas containing button-up and button-down 9-patches common to all buttons. The atlas also contains button-specific images that I superimpose on the 9-patches. I think it's important that the 9-patches are bigger than the buttons. Being left handed, I flip the camera and Atlas (or individual regions.) 

The result looks like a miscalculation in which some of the button-specific image has leaked into the 9-patch-only area and been stretched as if it were part of the 9-patch. 

Seems like a bug in TextureRegion.flip that affects 9-patches. My button code is as follows (It's in its own package so never mind the name clash on Button):

```
public class Button extends ImageButton {
static class Style {
    public ImageButtonStyle buttonstyle;
    Style(UiApp app, String id, char style, ChangeListener cl) {
        Sprite s_up = app.atlas.createSprite(id);
        Sprite s_down = new Sprite(s_up);
        s_down.setColor(0.7f, 0.7f, 0.7f, 1.0f);
        SpriteDrawable s_up_d = new SpriteDrawable(s_up);
        SpriteDrawable s_down_d = new SpriteDrawable(s_down);
        buttonstyle = new ImageButtonStyle(
                app.button_up,
                app.button_down,
                style=='s' ? app.button_down : app.button_up,
                s_up_d, 
                s_down_d,
                style=='s' ? s_down_d : s_up_d);

    }
}
public Button(UiApp app, String id, char style, ChangeListener cl) {
    super(new Style(app, id, style, cl).buttonstyle);
    if (cl!=null)
        addListener(cl);
}
```

}

That code relies on the app having loaded the 9-patches as follows:

```
    button_up = new NinePatchDrawable(atlas.createPatch("button_up"));
    button_down = new NinePatchDrawable(atlas.createPatch("button_down"));
```

